<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,342,267,293]" box="[189,342,267,293]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,267,293]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,267,293]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,1399,313,411]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
The species seems to be confined to the central islands of Santa Cruz, Seymour Norte, Santa Fé and Santiago. It has been found on Santa Cruz in the lower arid zone (
<quantity box="[951,1035,348,375]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="7.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="5.0">5-10 m</quantity>
alt.) and in the transition forest zone (
<quantity box="[260,388,384,411]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="180.0" valueMax="250.0" valueMin="110.0">110-250 m</quantity>
alt.), on Santiago in the transition forest at a higher elevation (
<quantity box="[1123,1199,384,411]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="580.0">580 m</quantity>
alt.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,303,449,475]" box="[189,303,449,475]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,449,475]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" reason="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,449,475]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[189,1399,496,768]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
The closely fused VTA and RTA of the male palpal tibia, the absence of a membranous area at the base of the embolus (# of 
<taxonomicName authority="C. L. Koch, 1837" authorityName="C. L. Koch" authorityYear="1837" box="[397,715,531,558]" class="Arachnida" family="Philodromidae" genus="Thanatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[397,506,531,557]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Thanatus</emphasis>
C. L. Koch, 1837
</taxonomicName>
), the equidistant posterior eyes (# of 
<taxonomicName authority="Simon, 1875" authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1875" box="[1141,1390,531,558]" class="Arachnida" family="Philodromidae" genus="Tibellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1141,1234,531,557]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Tibellus</emphasis>
Simon, 1875
</taxonomicName>
) and the elongated copulatory openings located at sides of septum (epigynal slits) reaching the epigynal fold in the female and the vulval conformation (spherical spermatheca and apical small spermatecal organ) observed in this galapagoan species, show it clearly belongs to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1122,1283,637,663]" class="Arachnida" family="Philodromidae" genus="Apollophanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1122,1283,637,663]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Apollophanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dondale C. D. &amp; Redner J. H." journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1175 - 1192" part="107" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.4039/Ent1071175-11" refString="Dondale C. D. &amp; Redner J. H. 1975. Revision of the spider genus Apollophanes (Araneida: Thomisidae). The Canadian Entomologist 107 (11): 1175 - 1192. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 1071175 - 11" title="Revision of the spider genus Apollophanes (Araneida: Thomisidae)" type="journal article" year="1975">Dondale &amp; Redner 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Muster C." box="[397,555,672,698]" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="47 - 73" part="16" publicationUrl="http://dx.doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.16.230" refString="Muster C. 2009. The Ebo - like running crab spiders in the Old World (Araneae, Philodromidae). ZooKeys 16: 47 - 73. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 16.230" title="The Ebo - like running crab spiders in the Old World (Araneae, Philodromidae)" type="journal article" year="2009">Muster 2009</bibRefCitation>
). It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="O.P. Cambridge, 1891" authorityName="O.P. Cambridge" authorityYear="1891" box="[735,1182,672,698]" class="Arachnida" family="Philodromidae" genus="Apollophanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctipes">
<emphasis box="[735,884,672,698]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">A. punctipes</emphasis>
(O.P. Cambridge, 1891)
</taxonomicName>
most closely, but a thorough examination of the male and female 
<typeStatus box="[800,851,708,734]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">type</typeStatus>
material of this species clearly showed the morphological differences between both species.
</paragraph>
